  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 3e1cd92da80c7495a8fe7eb91fa80c2f, type: 3}
  m_Name: Hibiscus
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::Plants.PlantData
  displayName: Hibiscus
  audioClip: {fileID: 8300000, guid: 308fb3101233a1947a984be73794e805, type: 3}
  environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
  poem:
    text: "Bol Re Joba Bol (Speak, O Hibiscus, Speak)\n\nUtter, O' rose mallow flower
      utter.\nWith which devotion at the feet of mother could you find shelter.\n\nBreaking
      shackles of illusive fetter, you fell on feet of the mother.\nYou got salvation,
      you bloom with joys and bewilder.\nYou teach me your devotion, O' mallow flower
      so that my life may\nprosper.\n\nBlooms a million flower in woods, hearts which
      wins over.\nHow could you find shelter under feet of mother, O rose mallow\nflower?\nI
      wish to turn ruddy under feet of the mother, when may I become\nflower to offer.\n\nWhen
      shall I turn red in color?\nO'dear, with touches of feet of the mother, When
      shall I turn red in\ncolor?\nWhen shall my heart like you shall stain with
      red color?\n\n\u2014 Kazu Nazrul Islam"
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
  contextInfos:
  - text: 'The red hibiscus is the flower of Maa Kali, the Hindu goddess of death
      and transformation. In Bengali art she appears wreathed in them, garlanded
      in red, goddess and flower merging in form. It is offered to her in worship.


      ![[Kali_by_Raja_Ravi_Varma.jpg]]https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Kali_by_Raja_Ravi_Varma.jpg'
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
  - text: 'Kazi Nazrul Islam - To the poets of the future

      To the Poets of
      the Future

      [Na-Asha-Diner Kabir Proti]


      O poets of the future,
      may you arise

      Like the morning sun,

      Bright and red like hibiscus
      blossoms.

      In the golden dawn for which we long

      May you wake up
      like countless flocks of birds.

      I sing in the hope that you will come

      To
      soar in the blue sky that I create.

      I leave behind the memory of my
      greetings to you:

      Play on my veena the song of the new day.'
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
  - text: 'hibiscus - matsuo basho

      in the twilight rain


      these brilliant-hued
      hibiscus


      a lovely sunset'
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
  - text: 'Hibiscus, Bengal

      The red hibiscus is the flower of Maa Kali, goddess
      of time, death, and transformation. Time is her dance, the universe unfolds
      and collapses in her steps. In Bengal she is approached as a mother: fierce
      and absolute, but one who protects and offers liberation to those who come
      to her as a child would. The hibiscus is offered to her in worship. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Kali_by_Raja_Ravi_Varma.jpg'
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
